In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app startup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android =>
    {
        android.OnPause(activity =>
        {
            // Runs when the Android activity is paused
        });
        android.OnStop(activity =>
        {
            // Runs when the Android activity is stopped
        });
    });
#endif

#if IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios =>
    {
        ios.DidEnterBackground(app =>
        {
            // Runs when the iOS app enters background
        });
    });
#endif
});
```

**Key points:**

- Call `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` on your `MauiAppBuilder`.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- You can also listen to the cross-platform `Window.Stopped` / `Window.Resumed` events if you don't need platform-specific details.
